        <rect x="290" y="203" width="120" height="37" rx="4" fill="#5D4FE0"/>
        <text x="350" y="195" text-anchor="middle" font-family="ui-sans-serif,system-ui,-apple-system" font-size="14" font-weight="700" fill="#5D4FE0">$44/yr</text>

        <!-- Bar 1 labels -->
        <text x="170" y="257" text-anchor="middle" font-family="ui-sans-serif,system-ui,-apple-system" font-size="12" font-weight="600" fill="#475569">Paid link</text>
        <text x="170" y="271" text-anchor="middle" font-family="ui-sans-serif,system-ui,-apple-system" font-size="10" fill="#94A3B8">$437 total · 2-year lifespan</text>
        <text x="170" y="283" text-anchor="middle" font-family="ui-sans-serif,system-ui,-apple-system" font-size="10" fill="#EF4444">deindex risk</text>

        <!-- Bar 2 labels -->
        <text x="350" y="257" text-anchor="middle" font-family="ui-sans-serif,system-ui,-apple-system" font-size="12" font-weight="600" fill="#475569">Earned mention</text>
        <text x="350" y="270" text-anchor="middle" font-family="ui-sans-serif,system-ui,-apple-system" font-size="10" fill="#64748B">heavy-hitting domain</text>
        <text x="350" y="283" text-anchor="middle" font-family="ui-sans-serif,system-ui,-apple-system" font-size="10" fill="#94A3B8">$437 total · 10-year+ lifespan</text>
        <text x="350" y="296" text-anchor="middle" font-family="ui-sans-serif,system-ui,-apple-system" font-size="10" fill="#5D4FE0">compound value</text>

      </svg>
      <p class="text-sm text-[#64748B] italic mt-3 text-center">Same $437 upfront. Different half-lives. The expensive option is the cheap one.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Pro Tip callout -->
    <div class="border-l-4 border-brand bg-white rounded-r-xl pl-5 pr-4 py-4 my-6 shadow-card">
      <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-ink mb-1">Pro tip</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-[#475569] leading-relaxed">When evaluating link spend, divide cost by useful lifespan. A $437 paid link with a two-year half-life costs more per useful year than a $437 earned mention on a heavy-hitting domain that survives every algorithm update.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- PROSE BLOCK 4: Evidence -->
    <div class="prose prose-lg text-body max-w-none space-y-6 leading-relaxed">

      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink leading-tight mt-10 mb-4">The Evidence</h2>
      <p>
        Google's March 2024 core update and every Helpful Content Update since have pushed harder on source authority and editorial quality. Marketplace domains have been purged in waves.
      </p>
      <p>
        Research on retrieval-augmented systems (the architecture behind every major AI answer engine) shows retrieval consistently weights sources that appear across multiple heavy-hitting domains over sources that appear once across many low-authority sites.
      </p>
      <p>
        On the pricing side, our longitudinal analysis of agency-managed link prices 2020–2026 shows the agency tier barely keeping pace with inflation while publisher-direct prices have tripled. The market is pricing in what indexation enforcement is doing to marketplace link value. Manufactured authority is getting cheaper because its shelf life is collapsing. Earned authority is getting more expensive because the durable supply is capped.
      </p>

    </div>

    <!-- Further Reading callout -->
    <div class="border-l-4 border-brand bg-white rounded-r-xl pl-5 pr-4 py-4 my-6 shadow-card">
      <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-ink mb-1">Further reading</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-[#475569] leading-relaxed"><a href="/resources/the-cost-of-authority" class="text-brand hover:text-brand-dark underline underline-offset-2">The Cost of Authority</a>: our pricing analysis of 140,000+ publisher listings across six years, showing exactly how agency-managed and publisher-direct link prices have moved 2020–2026.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- PROSE BLOCK 5: What This Means + Closing -->
    <div class="prose prose-lg text-body max-w-none space-y-6 leading-relaxed">

      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink leading-tight mt-10 mb-4">What This Means for B2B SaaS Marketing Teams</h2>
      <p>
        If your buyer is asking ChatGPT, Perplexity, Gemini, or Google's AI Overviews which tool to use in your category, your brand either shows up or doesn't. Paid links on marketplace sites will not put you in those answers. A pattern of earned mentions across the heavy-hitting domains in your category will.
      </p>
      <p class="font-semibold text-ink">The trajectory is set:</p>
      <p>
        Every B2B SaaS category will converge on this. The only variable is whether you build earned coverage before or after your competitors.
      </p>
      <p>
        The brands accumulating mentions on heavy-hitting domains now are the brands that will be surfaced as the defaults when their categories fully shift to AI-mediated search. That shift has already started.
      </p>
      <p>
        Stop buying links on marketplace sites. Redirect the budget into producing the kind of data, commentary, and expert insight that heavy-hitting domains want to cover. Earned coverage is slower to produce than a marketplace order. It is also the only output that survives the mechanism change.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink leading-tight mt-10 mb-4">Build Earned Coverage Before the Shift Finishes</h2>
      <p>
        AI systems will keep evolving. The domains they treat as heavy-hitters will keep changing. But the underlying principle does not move: brands mentioned across heavy-hitting domains get cited by AI.
      </p>
      <p>
        Paid links buy into a mechanism that is decaying. Earned coverage buys into the one that is replacing it.
      </p>
      <p>
        The only variable is whether you build it before or after your competitors.
      </p>
